          "input": "*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: /tmp/reme-issue-drafts/01-fetch-is-destructive-and-can-drop-messages.md\n+## Summary\n+\n+`GET /api/v1/fetch/:routing_key` deletes mailbox entries during fetch instead of after confirmed receipt. This makes message retrieval destructive and can permanently drop unread messages if the client crashes, times out, or fails during decode / storage after a successful fetch.\n+\n+## Why this matters\n+\n+This violates the current resilience contract:\n+\n+- `ROADMAP.md` says \"Messages never disappear silently\"\n+- `WHITEPAPER.md` documents the receive flow as fetch -> decrypt -> verify -> process DAG -> tombstone\n+\n+Right now the node removes messages inside fetch, before the client proves durable receipt.\n+\n+## Evidence\n+\n+- `crates/reme-node-core/src/mailbox_store.rs:425` fetches rows and collects IDs to delete\n+- `crates/reme-node-core/src/mailbox_store.rs:460` deletes fetched messages in the same call\n+- `apps/node/src/api.rs:629` exposes `state.store.fetch(&routing_key)` directly on the HTTP fetch endpoint\n+- `WHITEPAPER.md:173` describes tombstone after fetch/processing, not destructive fetch\n+- `ROADMAP.md:14` says client-side resilience comes first and messages must not disappear silently\n+\n+## Failure mode\n+\n+1. Client fetches messages successfully.\n+2. Node deletes them immediately.\n+3. Client crashes or fails before `process_message()` stores them and sends tombstones.\n+4. Messages are gone from all fetched nodes with no delivery proof.\n+\n+This gets worse in multi-node fetch because one node can be destructive even if the client ultimately fails on a different node's payload.\n+\n+## Proposed fix\n+\n+Change mailbox semantics from destructive fetch to tombstone-driven deletion:\n+\n+- `fetch` should return non-expired messages without deleting them\n+- tombstones should remain the only deletion path for delivered / retracted messages\n+- if duplicate delivery becomes a concern, track \"last served\" / visibility separately instead of deleting on read\n+\n+## Acceptance criteria\n+\n+- fetching a message does not remove it from the mailbox\n+- a message is removed only after a valid tombstone\n+- crash between fetch and client-side storage does not lose the message\n+- add integration coverage for: fetch + crash, repeated fetch before tombstone, tombstone after repeated fetch\n*** Add File: /tmp/reme-issue-drafts/02-multi-node-fetch-trusts-message-id-alone.md\n+## Summary\n+\n+Multi-node HTTP fetch deduplicates envelopes solely by `message_id`. If different relays return conflicting envelopes with the same `message_id`, the last one inserted wins, with no consistency check.\n+\n+## Why this matters\n+\n+The current threat model already includes compromised relays and active message injection / modification. A malicious or corrupted relay can overwrite a valid copy from another relay during aggregation and cause the client to discard the message before it ever reaches decryption.\n+\n+Combined with destructive fetch on the node side, this can become permanent message loss.\n+\n+## Evidence\n+\n+- `crates/reme-transport/src/http.rs:407` aggregates into `HashMap<MessageID, OuterEnvelope>`\n+- `crates/reme-transport/src/http.rs:421` does `messages_by_id.insert(msg.message_id, msg)`\n+- `crates/reme-transport/src/pool.rs:638` repeats the same logic for pooled HTTP targets\n+- `WHITEPAPER.md:80` threat model includes active attackers and compromised relays\n+\n+## Failure mode\n+\n+1. Relay A returns the legitimate envelope for `message_id = X`.\n+2. Relay B returns a tampered envelope with the same `message_id = X`.\n+3. Aggregation overwrites the first envelope with the second one.\n+4. Client only sees the poisoned copy and fails decryption / verification.\n+\n+There is no current safeguard that:\n+\n+- compares the conflicting envelopes\n+- preserves both copies for later validation\n+- prefers a quorum / majority copy\n+- flags relay divergence as suspicious\n+\n+## Proposed fix\n+\n+Treat `message_id` collisions with non-identical envelopes as a security event:\n+\n+- compare full envelope bytes or a stable envelope hash before deduplicating\n+- if copies differ, preserve all variants or mark the message as conflicted\n+- prefer a copy only after successful decryption / signature verification\n+- log or surface relay divergence for diagnostics\n+\n+## Acceptance criteria\n+\n+- two envelopes with the same `message_id` but different bytes are not silently collapsed\n+- fetch aggregation preserves enough information for the client to recover a valid copy\n+- add tests for conflicting relay responses on both `HttpTransport` and `TransportPool<HttpTarget>`\n*** Add File: /tmp/reme-issue-drafts/03-replication-authn-and-pin-verification-fail-open.md\n+## Summary\n+\n+Node-to-node replication is still fail-open in places where the codebase already advertises stronger guarantees. Peer configs can carry `cert_pin` and `node_pubkey`, but replication does not enforce either one. Signed-header destination verification is also optional and disabled by default.\n+\n+## Why this matters\n+\n+This is production-surface security, not future transport work:\n+\n+- replication is already part of current v0.3 behavior\n+- the whitepaper already claims HTTP transport with TLS / certificate pinning\n+- the code currently warns about insecure mode but proceeds anyway\n+\n+That leaves current replication traffic more vulnerable to misrouting / MITM than the rest of the design suggests.\n+\n+## Evidence\n+\n+- `crates/reme-config/src/validation.rs:131` includes `cert_pin`\n+- `crates/reme-config/src/validation.rs:135` includes `node_pubkey`\n+- `apps/node/src/replication.rs:31` builds a generic `reqwest::Client`\n+- `apps/node/src/replication.rs:137` leaves certificate pinning as TODO\n+- `apps/node/src/replication.rs:142` leaves peer identity verification as TODO\n+- `apps/node/src/config.rs:478` defaults `public_host` to `None`\n+- `apps/node/src/main.rs:160` only warns when destination verification is disabled\n+- `apps/node/src/signed_headers.rs:163` documents `public_host = None` as insecure mode\n+- `apps/node/src/signed_headers.rs:293` skips destination verification when `public_host` is absent\n+- `WHITEPAPER.md:859` says v0.3 transport includes TLS / certificate pinning\n+\n+## Failure mode\n+\n+- a pinned peer is configured but the replication client ignores the pin\n+- a known peer public key is configured but responses are not verified against it\n+- operators can run signed replication with destination binding effectively disabled\n+\n+## Proposed fix\n+\n+- wire per-peer certificate pinning into the replication client\n+- use configured `node_pubkey` to verify peer identity where applicable\n+- tighten startup / validation so identity-enabled replication without `public_host` is not silently accepted\n+- make insecure replication modes explicit opt-in, not implicit defaults\n+\n+## Acceptance criteria\n+\n+- configured `cert_pin` is enforced on replication requests\n+- configured `node_pubkey` is used for peer verification or the config rejects unsupported combinations\n+- identity-enabled replication no longer defaults to insecure destination verification\n+- startup / tests make the secure-vs-insecure mode boundary explicit\n*** Add File: /tmp/reme-issue-drafts/04-fetch-response-size-and-batch-shape-enable-dos.md\n+## Summary\n+\n+Mailbox fetch currently returns the entire mailbox as one base64-encoded JSON payload list. Given the current per-mailbox capacity and body-size limits, a hot mailbox can force large allocations and expensive encode/decode work on both node and client.\n+\n+## Why this matters\n+\n+This is a present-day availability issue on the current HTTP transport. It does not depend on future BLE / LoRa work.\n+\n+## Evidence\n+\n+- `apps/node/src/api.rs:53` sets `MAX_BODY_SIZE = 256 * 1024`\n+- `crates/reme-node-core/src/mailbox_store.rs:37` defaults `max_messages_per_mailbox` to `1000`\n+- `apps/node/src/api.rs:662` serializes every fetched envelope into one JSON response\n+- `crates/reme-transport/src/http.rs:392` fetches and aggregates full batches in memory\n+- `crates/reme-transport/src/http_target.rs:325` does the same per-target\n+\n+## Failure mode\n+\n+- a mailbox accumulates many near-limit envelopes\n+- fetch forces the node to base64-encode all of them at once\n+- the client allocates and decodes the whole response before any per-message handling\n+- high memory use and long response times become attacker-controlled\n+\n+## Proposed fix\n+\n+- add paging / batch size limits to fetch\n+- bound total serialized response size, not just request body size\n+- consider streaming or chunked fetch semantics for large mailboxes\n+- add server-side metrics / warnings for oversized mailbox fetches\n+\n+## Acceptance criteria\n+\n+- fetch supports bounded batches or pagination\n+- a single mailbox cannot force unbounded response growth within configured limits\n+- integration tests cover large mailbox retrieval without pathological memory amplification\n*** Add File: /tmp/reme-issue-drafts/05-pin-and-harden-github-actions-uses.md\n+## Summary\n+\n+The current GitHub Actions workflow uses floating action refs and leaves `actions/checkout` credential persistence at the default. `zizmor` reports this as 5 high-severity `unpinned-uses` findings and 2 medium `artipacked` findings.\n+\n+## Why this matters\n+\n+This is low implementation effort and removes avoidable CI supply-chain exposure before the repo grows more complex.\n+\n+## Evidence\n+\n+- `.github/workflows/lint.yml:26` uses `actions/checkout@v4`\n+- `.github/workflows/lint.yml:29` uses `dtolnay/rust-toolchain@stable`\n+- `.github/workflows/lint.yml:41` uses `actions/checkout@v4`\n+- `.github/workflows/lint.yml:44` uses `dtolnay/rust-toolchain@stable`\n+- `.github/workflows/lint.yml:49` uses `Swatinem/rust-cache@v2`\n+- `zizmor .github/workflows/` reports:\n+  - 5 `unpinned